                            <comment id="79695" author="amezick" created="Thu, 7 Jun 2012 13:10:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have been thinking about this more.  I think the problem is that what is stored in the $&lt;/p&gt;
{page.number} property of the PageImpl class is not the page number.  The value stored is what needs to be used to calculate the offset.  Right now, to create paging links I have to do:&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;p/&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;syntaxplugin&quot; class=&quot;syntaxplugin&quot; style=&quot;border: 1px dashed #bbb; border-radius: 5px !important; overflow: auto; max-height: 30em;&quot;&gt;
&lt;table cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em !important; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; color: black;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;tbody &gt;
				&lt;tr id=&quot;syntaxplugin_code_and_gutter&quot;&gt;
						&lt;td  style=&quot; line-height: 1.4em !important; padding: 0em; vertical-align: top;&quot;&gt;
					&lt;pre style=&quot;font-size: 1em; margin: 0 10px;  margin-top: 10px;   margin-bottom: 10px;  width: auto; padding: 0;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/pre&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;a href=&quot;url?page.page=${page.number}
&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;BACK&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;a href=&quot;url?page.page=$&lt;/p&gt;
{page.number+1}
&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;REFRESH&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;&lt;br/&gt;
&amp;lt;a href=&quot;url?page.page=$&lt;/p&gt;
{page.number+2}
&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt;NEXT&amp;lt;/a&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p/&gt;
&lt;div id=&quot;syntaxplugin&quot; class=&quot;syntaxplugin&quot; style=&quot;border: 1px dashed #bbb; border-radius: 5px !important; overflow: auto; max-height: 30em;&quot;&gt;
&lt;table cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; width=&quot;100%&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 1em; line-height: 1.4em !important; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; color: black;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;tbody &gt;
				&lt;tr id=&quot;syntaxplugin_code_and_gutter&quot;&gt;
						&lt;td  style=&quot; line-height: 1.4em !important; padding: 0em; vertical-align: top;&quot;&gt;
					&lt;pre style=&quot;font-size: 1em; margin: 0 10px;  margin-top: 10px;   margin-bottom: 10px;  width: auto; padding: 0;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/pre&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
			&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p/&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(can&apos;t seem to get this tag to work.)&lt;br/&gt;
Add 1 to stay on the same page and 2 to go to the next page.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="89343" author="olivergierke" created="Fri, 12 Apr 2013 03:03:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is (was) intended behavior actually. The &lt;tt&gt;Page&lt;/tt&gt; API is zero-indexed (as indicated in the JavaDocs), the web API is 1 indexed (to be more human readable). This was done assuming you&apos;d wrap the &lt;tt&gt;Page&lt;/tt&gt; into a web-related DTO or the like anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You might wanna have a look at the &lt;tt&gt;PageableHandlerMethodArgumentResolver&lt;/tt&gt; introduced in the master branch which essentially supersedes the &lt;tt&gt;PageableArgumentResolver&lt;/tt&gt; and uses zero-index page parameters. Let me know what you think.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="92474" author="olivergierke" created="Tue, 6 Aug 2013 06:22:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Are you still affected by this behavior when using the newly introduced &lt;tt&gt;PageableHandlerMethodArgumentResolver&lt;/tt&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="92983" author="olivergierke" created="Wed, 21 Aug 2013 23:49:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Should be fixed with the introduction of &lt;tt&gt;PageableHandlerMethodArgumentResolver&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
